 remarkable diversity of American religion and the intricate ways it interacted with the broader culture. Longenecker argues that Gettysburg religion revealed much about larger American society and about how trends in the Border North mirrored national developments. In many ways, Gettysburg and its surrounding Border North religion belonged to the future and signaled a coming pattern for modern America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aReligion and culturezPennsylvaniazGettysburg RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aReligion and culturezPennsylvaniazGettysburgxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh  aAfrican American (Black).  aCivil War.  aCivil religion.  aDiversity.  aEvangelicalism.  aGettysburg.  aLutheran.  aPennsylvania.  aRace.  arefinement.1 aCatherine, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmucker, Steenbergen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimon, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z97831111896040 cprintz978082325519140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823255214?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823255214423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823255214/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEB